PlaybackHeartbeat

|- The PlaybackHeartbeat event is fired for the following reasons: 1. Heartbeats should be fired immediately after playback has started or resumed. 2. Heartbeats should be fired immediately before playback paused, or playback ended in order to capture duration of playback immediately before playback ends for any reason. 3. Periodic heartbeats should begin to send once playback has started. The expected frequency is every 30 seconds of wall clock time that has passed since the last playbackHeartbeat event was fired. 4. While playback is paused the following rules should apply: - If no playback has happened in the last 30 seconds, don't fire a heartbeat - This should be throttled to not send when the playback_duration is 0 to reduce low value traffic from paused devices. - Heartbeats with sampleType=user are permitted during a paused state to capture user actions as they happen, e.g. audio or subtitle track switching. 5. The following value changes should trigger a playbackHeartbeat event while playback is ocurring. Only sampleType=user playbackHeartbeat events should be sent while playback is paused: - cpSessionId -> This will never change as the player is deallocated between sessions - playbackSessionId -> This will never change as the player is deallocated between sessions - streamUrl (from playlist) -> Fired right before player_segment_end - contentId (from eab_id in bundle metadata) -> Fired right before player_segment_end - presentationType (from manifest/player) -> Fired right before changing presentations of any type, where the reported presentationType is that of the upcoming content - periodType (from manifest/player) -> Fired right before entering interstitials of any type (deprecated in favor of 'presentationType) - cdnName - videoBitrate - playlistSubtitleLanguage (implying sampleType=user) - playlistSubtitleName (implying sampleType=user) - subtitleVisibility (implying sampleType=user) - playlistAudioChannels (implying sampleType=user) - playlistAudioCodec (implying sampleType=user) - playlistAudioLanguage (implying sampleType=user) - playlistAudioName (implying sampleType=user) - playbackMode (implying sampleType=user)

type: urn:cs:event:pq:playback:v1:playback-heartbeat

required
number <double>

Duration of the playback since last player_heartbeat event in milliseconds, regardless of presentationType.

playbackState
required
string (PlaybackState)
Enum: "paused" "buffering" "finished" "playing" "seeking"
totalVst
required
number <double>

The total time from the playlist configuration service request to either: - the first time unit render - the player fully buffered and ready, in the case of preloading

This is instrumented in the L2 player, in particular:
- Timing begins with the value of videoStartTimestamp
- Timing ends at the start of playback

If this value is not available at the time the event is being sent, please pass 0.
videoStartTimestamp
required
number <double>

The client epoch timestamp of requesting playlist configuration service. If this value is not available at the time the event is being sent, please pass 0.

bufferSegmentDuration
required
number

Amount of video currently fully buffered in milliseconds. Best version is accessed via a getter provided by logic player. Much-better-than-nothing version is the last value provided in the TimeUpdated event (where the biggest problem it has is not updating while the player is paused, but heartbeat is still reporting).

If this value is not available at the time the event is being sent, please pass 0.
mediaBytesDownloaded
required
number <double>

Sum of all bytes downloaded since the last player heartbeat for all the following resource types: - Manifests (M3U8 or MPD) - Video segments - Audio segments - Muxed video/audio segments - Timed text (subtitle) segments or sidecar files - Thumbnail images or I-frame segments

to represent bytes played instead.

If data about all listed resource types is not available, clients should use best effort to include as many listed resource types as possible.

Value is the number of bytes
mediaDownloadTotalTime
required
number <double>

Sum of time spent for all media bytes downloaded since the last player heartbeat event. “All media” here means all media resources, mainly including video segments and audio segments.

mediaDownloadTotalCount
required
number <double>

Number of all downloaded (including successfully and failed) video and audio segments.

Time in seconds from the beginning of the content when the user exited the video.

cpSessionId
required
string

Client generated ID of the continuous play. Only resets if the person leaves the player.

cpVideoIndex
required
number

0 based index of the video being played for the same cpSessionId. Increments every time the playback event with playbackActivity of 'started' is sent (such that the 'started' event has the incremented value).

productType
required
string

Product type, Live or VOD. Product type comes in the playlist response, but the SDK controls the serialization for this specific field. It is received from MediaApi.initializePlaybackContext() and used instead of the playlist response's value so the field can be supplied on all playback startup events.

videoBitrate
required
number

Nominal peak (encoded) bitrate of the currently selected presentationType or of the presentationType/variant last played, as reported in the HLS or DASH manifest. For HLS Manifest, use the 'BANDWIDTH' value and for DASH, use the '@bandwidth' value.

If value is 0 or not available return 0.

If value is muxed, send the bitrate of the combined content.
audioBitrate
required
number

Nominal average (encoded) bitrate of the currently selected presentationType or of the presentationType/variant last played before the event, as reported in the HLS or DASH manifest.

If value is 0 or not available return 0.

If value is muxed, send the bitrate of the combined content.
maxAllowedVideoBitrate
required
number <double>

The highest video bitrate available for the currently selected presentationType in the current DASH/HLS manifest that is allowed to play. For HLS Manifest, use the 'BANDWIDTH' value and for DASH, use the '@bandwidth' value.

max_allowed_video_bitrate should be updated at least once per period.

Clients like Web, iOS and Android should also update it if the player imposes a bitrate or resolution cap based
on data saver setting or video window resolution/orientation.

Clients should check this value throughout playback because the value can change if, for example, the video window is
resized or the video quality is constrained by the user.

Value is a number in bits per second. If value is muxed, send the bitrate of the combined content.

The value should default to 0 if unavailable or unknown.

The session will be terminated when the app is closed, browser is closed, the app has idled/been backgrounded for too long (determined in https://jira.bamtechmedia.com/browse/DMGZ-1859), user changes devices or upon log out. Unique identifier of the specific view of this page for the specific user. A new pageViewId will be generated when a user returns to a page they've already visited (i.e. upon back nav).

-- Examples --
- VJ's pageView of the pixar collection must have a different pageViewId than his daughter's pageView of it.
- When VJ views pixar collection > content detail > back to pixar, the pageViewId for pixar will be different as a new pageViewId will be generated.
- When VJ views home > marvel collection > avengers endgame > clicks Home menu_item, the pageViewId will be different for both home page views.

Onboarding screens have pageName values that are not 'collection', 'movie_details', 'series_details', 'video_player', 'whos_watching', 'add_profile', 'edit_profile'. If pageName value references 'host_groupwatch_room', 'host_groupwatch_invite_link_modal', 'guest_groupwatch_room', contentKeys values should reflect the content that the group is streaming. GroupWatch screens have pageName values that contain 'groupwatch'.

monotonicTimestamp
number

Timestamp in milliseconds (relative to when the device was booted, or some other fixed time origin) when the record was captured. The underlying clock used for this should be monotonic and should continue to tick even when the device is in sleep mode (where possible). Platforms without a clock implementation that fully meets the requirements should utilize a timer whereby the value of the timestamp strictly increases across events in the same session, even if the timer only operates in the foreground or has other limitations. The intent of this field is to capture values that can be used to calculate accurate time intervals across events, as other timestamps are subject to local clock changes and may fluctuate.

liveLatencyAmount
number

Latency of the current playback position with the live head (live head - current position, >= 0) in milliseconds (ms).

When user clicks `go to live` button on player UI, this value would be cleared to 0. Live head here means the latest time position that the player is allowed to seek to.
Live head does not necessarily need to be the latest timestamp in manifest.

This value should default to 0 if unknown or not available.
segmentPosition
number

Current location in the current segment. If live video, this should be the epoch time in milliseconds of the video. The default value should be 0 if unknown or unavailable.

number
  •                  For primary content. As defined by the BANDWIDTH (where available) of the
                 highest bitrate variant attained during a viewer session. For HLS
                 Manifest, use the 'BANDWIDTH' value and for DASH, use the '@bandwidth'
                 value.
                 maxAttainedBitrate should be updated at least once per period (per heartbeat).
                 Value is a number in bits per second. If value is muxed, send the bitrate of the combined content.
                 If value is 0 or not available return 0.
                 Example via heartbeat event
                 `│ time │ videoBitrate │ maxAttainedBitrate │`
                 `│ t0   │ 1200000      │ 1200000            │`
                 `│ t1   │ 1200000      │ 1200000            │`
                 `│ t2   │ 1800000      │ 1800000            │`
                 `│ t3   │ 1800000      │ 1800000            │`
                 `│ t4   │ 1800000      │ 1800000            │`
                 `│ t5   │ 2400000      │ 2400000            │`
                 `│ t6   │ 1200000      │ 2400000            │`

Error

This event should be sent out every time there is an error in the application as soon as it's known. This event should be used for a variety of different errors and should be differentiated by the applicationContext. For applicationContext=player, errors that lead to playback stopping or being blocked are fatal, otherwise they are non-fatal. Errors will be categorized more clearly in future error mapping projects.

max_allowed_video_bitrate should be updated at least once per period.

Clients like Web, iOS and Android should also update it if the player imposes a bitrate or resolution cap based
on data saver setting or video window resolution/orientation.

Clients should check this value throughout playback because the value can change if, for example, the video window is
resized or the video quality is constrained by the user.

Value is a number in bits per second. If value is muxed, send the bitrate of the combined content.

The value should default to 0 if unavailable or unknown.

PlaybackStartUp

This event should be sent every time the playbackActivity changes. The first event that is sent should be requested. Note that once playback has started, playbackStartup events must no longer fire. The first event that is sent should be requested. Possible start up events include:

  • requested
  • ready
  • initialized
  • fetched
  • masterFetched
  • variantFetched
  • drmCertificateFetched
  • drmKeyFetched
  • reattempt

requested should be sent when the user initiates play, either click, tap, or system. playbackSessionId is generated when this event is sent. Represents an action of selecting a media to play, capturing intent to play content, leading into video playback. This activity represents intent to play video. Happens before playlist request as the first event in the series of events leading to video playback. ready should be sent when the player is ready to play. Generated when enough media has been buffered for playback to begin. initialized should be sent when the player initializes with a playlist. fetched should be sent when there is a fetch of a resource on the network. This event represents a call to Playlist Service to get information about a stream. masterFetched should be sent when there is a fetch of a resource on the network. This event represents a fetch of the master m3u8. variantFetched should be sent when there is a fetch of a resource on the network. This event represents a fetch of a variant m3u8. For both Live & VOD, only send the variantFetched in the following cases:

  • during startup phase
  • associated with bitrate switching, such as fetching of new variants due to ABR logic. For Live, stop sending the regular variantFetched event during playback. drmCertificateFetched should be sent when there is a fetch of a resource on the network. This event represents a fetch of a DRM certificate. drmKeyFetched should be sent when there is a fetch of a resource on the network. This event represents a fetch of a DRM key. reattempt represents an indicaton of a subsequent systematic reattempt playback due to non fatal playback cases, including CDN fallback. Refer: https://lucid.app/lucidchart/8158cec9-f086-4b1a-aa47-a35ee2342402/view?page=0_0#

monotonicTimestamp
number

Timestamp in milliseconds (relative to when the device was booted, or some other fixed time origin) when the record was captured. The underlying clock used for this should be monotonic and should continue to tick even when the device is in sleep mode (where possible). Platforms without a clock implementation that fully meets the requirements should utilize a timer whereby the value of the timestamp strictly increases across events in the same session, even if the timer only operates in the foreground or has other limitations. The intent of this field is to capture values that can be used to calculate accurate time intervals across events, as other timestamps are subject to local clock changes and may fluctuate.

required
number

Timestamp in milliseconds relative to when the device was booted, or some other fixed time origin when the record was captured. The underlying clock used for this should be monotonic and should continue to tick even when the device is in sleep mode where possible. Platforms without a clock implementation that fully meets the requirements should utilize a timer whereby the value of the timestamp strictly increases across events in the same session, even if the timer only operates in the foreground or has other limitations. The intent of this field is to capture values that can be used to calculate accurate time intervals across events, as other timestamps are subject to local clock changes and may fluctuate.

cause
string (Cause)
Enum: "applicationExit" "applicationBackground" "user" "error" "playedToEnd" "stall" "applicationBackgrounded" "applicationForegrounded" "app" "skip" "seek" "scrub" "startAtBookmark"

The reason for ending playback, pausing, seeking or resuming.

playback end applicationExit, when the application was terminated during playback. applicationBackground, when the application was sent to background during playback. Note if playback continues in PiP, it is not considered to have ended. user, when the user exits the player. error, when a fatal error occurs which prevents playback from continuing. playedToEnd, when the media plays to completion and the player automatically closes.

pause user, if the user pressed pause or pressed play. stall, if the player paused due to insufficient buffer. applicationBackground, when the application was sent to background during playback. Note if playback continues in PiP, it is not considered backgrounded.

resume user, if the user pressed play from a paused state. stall, if the player buffered enough to resume playback. applicationForegrounded, where the application is brought to foreground after being previously background. For Apple, when the app transitions from PiP mode to the application, is applicationWillEnterForeground() or sceneWillEnterForeground() triggered? If so, then send the applicationForegrounded event.

seek app when the player jumps to live or the application decides the target playhead. skip when the user skips to a milestone (intro skip, recap end, or +/- x second skips). seek when the user seeks to a specific point by tapping on the timeline or dragging the playhead to a new position on the timeline. scrub when a new position is reached via linear reverse or forward playback at a non-1x rate. startAtBookmark when there is a seek event sent prior to playback started, which can occur on instances like 'continue watching'.

PlaybackSnapshot

Playback Snapshot Event provides deeper insights to drill down into issues and improve QoS algorithms. QoS algorithms include client-side ABR (adaptive bitrate) and server-side decisioning algorithms. Playback Snapshot Event contains information about media resource downloading and player status during playback sessions, such as: - Data of downloading each video / audio media fragments, like elapsed time, byte sizes, status code, instant network bandwidth, etc. - Instant data of low-level player status, including buffered fragment duration, transitions between rebuffering and playing, current used CDN, etc. - If PQM (or other ABR algorithm modules) are enabled (specifically on HiVE and NVE players), its decisions and corresponding reasons for each media fragments downloading, including CDN switching, adaptive bitrate switching, error handling, etc. - Indispensable metadata for the current playback session, including bitrate profile ladders, candidate CDN lists, etc. PlaybackSnapshot is fired for two reasons: - When there are enough snapshotEvent objects to report (initially 10, but value is configurable by SDKs). - Immediately before playback end. This includes VSF, VPF, and EBVS scenarios and when there are no snapshotEvent objects to report upon playback ending.

type: urn:cs:event:pq:playback:v1:playback-snapshot

PlaybackEvent

This event should be sent every time the playbackActivity changes. The first event that is sent should be started.

 Possible playback events include:
 - started
 - rebufferingStarted
 - rebufferingEnded
 - seekStarted
 - seekEnded
 - paused
 - resumed
 - ended
 - bitrateChanged
 - variantFetched
 started should be sent when the first frame of the stream is rendered, regardless of presentationType (e.g. bumper, ad, main, etc.)
 rebufferingStarted should be sent when video playback is buffering for any reason (ex. video startup or any connection reasons).
 This happens anytime the buffer is depleted to the point where playback cannot continue and can happen during normal
 playback or when seeking outside the range of buffered content. If rebuffering happens as a result of a presentationType change,
 the reported presentationType should be that of the upcoming content.
 rebufferingEnded should be sent when buffering has ended (after player buffer start).
 seekStarted should be sent every time the user commits to a new seek position. (Commit = No further user confirmation is needed.
 On mobile, every 'double-tap' is a committed seek. On CD's, timeline scrubbing is not committed until the user takes an action.)
 The content position should be the value(s) from BEFORE the seek has modified it.
 seekEnded should be sent as soon as it tells the L2 player to actually seek to that new position.
 In most cases, that should be every seekStarted unless the L1 has explicit debouncing logic to coalesce seek requests.
 Implications are as follows:
 1. Every successful seek must have 1 seekEnded and 1 corresponding seekStarted that has the same properties (position, direction, source, etc.).
 2. If the L1 player is debouncing seek events, it is acceptable for there to be a seekStarted event without a matching seekEnded event if and only if
 there is a subsequent seekStarted event that is paired with a corresponding seekEnded event. The content position should be the value(s) from AFTER the seek has modified it.
 paused should be sent when playback is paused
 - long press while scrubbing
 - pressing the pause button while playback is occurring
 - 'are you still watching?' dialog appears
 - There is a signal that indicates the HDMI cable was pulled or the tv was turned off
 - In a groupwatch session after seeking, the player is paused to allow other members to sync
 Needed so that someone who has access to the event stream can tell that playback had paused
 resumed should be sent when playback has resumed after pausing but not after buffering. The event is also triggered when player stops fast-forwarding or rewinding.
 ended should be sent when playback ends. This may be caused by an error preventing playback, a user exiting playback, or an error which causes playback to fail.
 This event should have a corresponding started event. If the user exits the stream before any content is shown, neither an ended nor started should be fired for that content session.
 For Android specifically, this hit should not be triggered when the app is sent to the background by either pressing the device home button or by opening the tasks manager, or by any other way to send the app to the background.
 Once the ended event is sent, no other events should be sent out for that playbackSessionId.
 bitrateChanged should be sent when the video bitrate of a piece of content changes.
 variantFetched should only be subsequent to audio, subtitle or bitrate changes require a new variant. These should not be sent for update playlist in live content. They should continue to be sent via the startup event, for the startup phase.

playback end applicationExit, when the application was terminated during playback. applicationBackground, when the application was sent to background during playback. Note if playback continues in PiP, it is not considered to have ended. user, when the user exits the player. error, when a fatal error occurs which prevents playback from continuing. playedToEnd, when the media plays to completion and the player automatically closes.

pause user, if the user pressed pause or pressed play. stall, if the player paused due to insufficient buffer. applicationBackground, when the application was sent to background during playback. Note if playback continues in PiP, it is not considered backgrounded.

resume user, if the user pressed play from a paused state. stall, if the player buffered enough to resume playback. applicationForegrounded, where the application is brought to foreground after being previously background. For Apple, when the app transitions from PiP mode to the application, is applicationWillEnterForeground() or sceneWillEnterForeground() triggered? If so, then send the applicationForegrounded event.

seek app when the player jumps to live or the application decides the target playhead. skip when the user skips to a milestone (intro skip, recap end, or +/- x second skips). seek when the user seeks to a specific point by tapping on the timeline or dragging the playhead to a new position on the timeline. scrub when a new position is reached via linear reverse or forward playback at a non-1x rate. startAtBookmark when there is a seek event sent prior to playback started, which can occur on instances like 'continue watching'.

AdPlayback

This event should be sent every time the adActivity changes. Note: In addition to the explicit requirements outlined in the event spec, clients should also send the following properties under these conditions: - adVideoData: recommended when adActivity = 'adVariantFetched' AND mediaSegmentType = 'video' - adAudioData: recommended when adActivity = 'adVariantFetched' AND mediaSegmentType = 'audio' - adSubtitleData: recommended when adActivity = 'adVariantFetched' AND mediaSegmentType = 'subtitle' - adErrorData: recommended when adActivity = 'adPlaybackEnded' AND cause = 'error' Note: In addition to the descriptions for each individual field, the following guidelines provide additional specificity: - adStartupData: - when adActivity = 'adPodFetched': startTimestamp should equal the monotonicTimestamp of the preceding ad playback event where adActivity = 'adPodRequested' and requestDuration is the difference between that timestamp and the current event's monotonicTimestamp - when adActivity = 'adMultivariantFetched': startTimestamp is the monotonicTimestamp when the multivariant playlist is requested and requestDuration is the difference between that timestamp and the current event's monotonicTimestamp - when adActivity = 'adVariantFetched': startTimestamp is the monotonicTimestamp when the variant playlist is requested and requestDuration is the difference between that timestamp and the current event's monotonicTimestamp

type: urn:cs:event:pq:playback:v1:ad-playback

adActivity
required
string (AdActivity)
Enum: "adPodRequested" "adPodFetched" "adMultivariantFetched" "adVariantFetched" "adPlaybackStarted" "adPlaybackEnded"

Used to identify what ad-related activity is occurring in playback. Criteria for when an event should be sent for each activity is as follows: - adPodRequested: when clients make a request via getPodRequest to the Disney Ad Server, applicable to SGAI-supporting clients only - adPodFetched: when clients receive a response from the Disney Ad Server for getPodRequest, applicable to SGAI-supporting clients only - adMultivariantFetched: when a multivariant playlist has been downloaded, applicable to SGAI-supporting clients only - adVariantFetched: when a variant playlist has been downloaded, applicable to SGAI-supporting clients only - adPlaybackStarted: when the first frame has been displayed for each ad slot, applicable to all ad-supporting clients - adPlaybackEnded: when playback completes for any reason (e.g., successful playback to end, user exit before/during playback, or playback failure) for each ad slot, applicable to all ad-supporting clients

monotonicTimestamp
required
number

Timestamp in milliseconds (relative to when the device was booted, or some other fixed time origin) when the record was captured. The underlying clock used for this should be monotonic and should continue to tick even when the device is in sleep mode (where possible). Platforms without a clock implementation that fully meets the requirements should utilize a timer whereby the value of the timestamp strictly increases across events in the same session, even if the timer only operates in the foreground or has other limitations. The intent of this field is to capture values that can be used to calculate accurate time intervals across events, as other timestamps are subject to local clock changes and may fluctuate.

cause
string (Cause)
Enum: "applicationExit" "applicationBackground" "user" "error" "playedToEnd" "stall" "applicationBackgrounded" "applicationForegrounded" "app" "skip" "seek" "scrub" "startAtBookmark"

The reason for ending playback, pausing, seeking or resuming.

playback end applicationExit, when the application was terminated during playback. applicationBackground, when the application was sent to background during playback. Note if playback continues in PiP, it is not considered to have ended. user, when the user exits the player. error, when a fatal error occurs which prevents playback from continuing. playedToEnd, when the media plays to completion and the player automatically closes.

pause user, if the user pressed pause or pressed play. stall, if the player paused due to insufficient buffer. applicationBackground, when the application was sent to background during playback. Note if playback continues in PiP, it is not considered backgrounded.

resume user, if the user pressed play from a paused state. stall, if the player buffered enough to resume playback. applicationForegrounded, where the application is brought to foreground after being previously background. For Apple, when the app transitions from PiP mode to the application, is applicationWillEnterForeground() or sceneWillEnterForeground() triggered? If so, then send the applicationForegrounded event.

seek app when the player jumps to live or the application decides the target playhead. skip when the user skips to a milestone (intro skip, recap end, or +/- x second skips). seek when the user seeks to a specific point by tapping on the timeline or dragging the playhead to a new position on the timeline. scrub when a new position is reached via linear reverse or forward playback at a non-1x rate. startAtBookmark when there is a seek event sent prior to playback started, which can occur on instances like 'continue watching'.

The version of the running application

platform

The SDK platform

platformId
string

The platformId value on the SDKs is derived from the SDK configs, which is used by the Playlist Service to return the plt in Conviva data, which they retrieve from the token, which likely receives its value from the device grant metadata. The following wiki documents how this value is generated across each SDK platform: https://wiki.disneystreaming.com/display/SDKC/SDK+Platform+Values+Reporting+Documentation

Indicates whether the playlist contains slugs. Should default to false.

string

|- /md UUID representing a single element interaction within the container. The interactionId will correspond with one of the above interactionTypes. The interactionId will be used as the primary key for all interactions. Reference FEDSA docs for UUID creation.

string

DSS identifier cross partners. (D+/Hulu/ESPN/Star+)

mediaFetchSucceeded
boolean

A flag indicating if the media fetch request to the playback orchestration service succeeded.

sessionId
string

Id of the session generating event

hasPromos
boolean

Indicates whether the playlist contains promos. Should default to false.

pboVersion
number

Version of PBO (PlayIO) service used to orchestrate content delivery, including interstitials i.e. ads, bumpers.

hasNetworkBumpers
boolean

This indicates that the playback session included a network attribution pre-roll inserted via SGAI/SSAI into the playlist.

hasTuneInCards
boolean

This indicates that the session includes a tune in card, inserted via SGAI/SSAI into the playlist.

hasAds
boolean

This indicates that the playback session included a network attributio pre-roll inserted via SGAI/SSAI into the playlist. Based upon rule match that ad-server-was-called AND ad-server returned one or more planned breaks.

hasDisclaimers
boolean

This indicates that the session includes a disclaimers inserted via SGAI/SSAI into the playlist e.g. inclusion of ads in content (which would be served to customer both in and out of the ads tiers).

containsSmashed
boolean

Providing indication that an asset has been smashed (Hulu segmented output)

viewingEnvironment
string

Viewing environments are 360 degree immersive spaces that transport the user into a full screen disney experience. For MVP launch we will have five brand-specific Viewing Environments backdrops: Disney, Star Wars, Marvel, Pixar, National Geographic.

            How will this field be provided?
            By client > SDK > PQoE > PQ

            ex. disney, star_wars, marvel, pixar, nat_geo, default
            conditionally required on platformId = realitydevice
contentPresentation
string

Whether the content is 2d or 3d
